<section xml:id="section-activity-clo5">
  <title>Activity for CLO-5</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo5-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What do we means in mathematic with the word <sq>model</sq>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We mean applying a mathematical construction to describe a
          real-world situation. In thist course, that construction is
          a function: we use a particular function to describe the
          relationship between two real-world quantities. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Why is a mathematical model like a scientific hypothesis?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A scientific hypothesis is a claim about some piece of
          observable and measurable phenomenoon. A mathematcal model
          is the example of such a claim: it is claiming that two
          quantities in the world relate to each other in a way that
          is described by a mathematical function (within some margin
          of error, at least). Like a scientific hypothesis, a
          mathematical model may be accurate or inaccurate. It may
          describe the world well or describe the world poorly.
          Evidence can be gathered to support or to undermine the
          value of the model. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Why do models often have additional domain restrictions?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          When I choose a mathematical function as a model, that
          function will have a mathematically determined domain. This
          is just the rule of mathematics: no division by zero, no
          even roots of negative numbers, and so on. However, when a
          function becomes a model, the reasonable values of the
          quantities are restricted by the situation. If I am
          measuring distances or population, then negative numbers are
          unreasonable. If I am measuring time, then there is probably
          a limit to how far back in time I can reasonably look. If I
          am measuring temperature in degrees Celcius, then the lowest
          possible value is <m>-273</m>. These become additional
          domain restrictions imposed by the situation of the mdoel
          instead of just the mathematical rules of domains. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What does <sq>regression</sq> mean as a mathematical term. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A regression is a way of determining a relationship between
          two quantities in the real world. In the language of this
          course, it is a method for choosing a function as a model of
          some situation. The methods of regression are mostly part of
          statistics, not calculus, though calculus is heavily
          involved in the background of those methods. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are the important properties of exponential groth. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          As a function, exponential growth is a model where time is
          the exponent in ane exponential expression. It can also be
          described by a consistent doubling period, adjusting the
          exponential expression so that the exponential base becomes
          <m>2</m>. Finally and most importantly, exponential
          regression seems to match up with a situation where the
          growth per unit of time is a percentage of the total:
          exponential growth and percentage growth appear to be the
          same phenomenonon. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
