  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-interpreting-parameters">
    <title>Interpreting Parameters</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
        Consider <m>C(t) = ae^{-bt}</m>, a model of the concentration
        of a chemical over time. Give an interpretation for the
        parameters <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> in this model. Assume that
        the parameters are positive.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
        This is the same form as the exponential form for population
        growth, but with a negative exponent. I can use our
        undersatnding of the parameters in population growth to
        interpret these parameters. When <m>t=0</m>, I have <m>C(0) =
        a</m>, so <m>a</m> the starting value. The coefficient in the
        exponential was the rate of exponential growth for population.
        I can likewise conclude that <m>b</m> is control the rate of
        decay of concentration here. This is decay because there is a 
        negative exponential. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
        Consider <m>p(d) = a + bd</m>, a model of the pressure in a
        body of water as a function of depth. Give an interpretation
        for the parameters <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> in this model. Assume
        that the parameters are positive.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
        When the depth is zero, I have <m>p(0) = a</m>. I can
        conclude that <m>a</m> is the pressure at the surface of the
        body of water. Since the parameters are positive, this
        pressure increases linearly as the depth increases. The
        parameter <m>b</m> is the slope of this increas, so it measure
        that rate of which the water gains pressure as depth
        increases.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
        Consider <m>h(t) = a + b\sin(\pi t) - ct</m>, a model of
        height of an object as a function of time. Give an
        interpretation for the parameters <m>a</m>, <m>b</m> and
        <m>c</m>in this model. Assume that the parameters are
        positive.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
        When the time is 0, I have <m>p(0) = a</m>. Therefore, I can
        call <m>a</m> the starting height. The other pieces of the
        function are sinusoidal oscillation linear decline. The
        parameter <m>b</m> is the amplitude of the sinusoidal piece
        and the parameter <m>c</m> is the negative slope of the linear
        decline. The behaviour of the model comes from adding these
        two behaviours together: so I get some oscillations while
        generally having a linear decline. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
        Consider <m>p(t) = (a-b)t + c</m>, a model of population as a
        function of time. Give an interpretation for the parameters
        <m>a</m>, <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> in this model. Assume that the
        parameters are positive.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
        When time is 0, I have <m>p(0) = c</m>, so <m>c</m> is the
        starting value of the population. The population is linear,
        with slope <m>a-b</m>. This will be positive or negative
        depending on which parameter is larger. Since the parater
        <m>a</m> is positive but I subtract the parameter <m>b</m>,
        <m>a</m> must have a positive effect on the population and
        <m>b</m> must have a negative effect. The simpliest way to
        interpret this is to assume that <m>a</m> is a birth rate and
        <m>b</m> is a death rate. The population will only grow if the
        rate of briths exceeds the rate of deaths. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-exponential-regression">
    <title>Calculation Questions: Exponential Regression </title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Here is a dataset. Just by looking at the dataset, guess
          the doubling period and write a guess of the appropriate
          exponential function. Evaluate that exponential function
          (using a calculator or computer) and compare the values with
          the data. 
          <table xml:id="table-data-set-exponential-1">
            <title>Data Set 1 for Exponential Growth</title>
            <tabular>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell right="medium">t</cell>
                <cell>0</cell>
                <cell>1</cell>
                <cell>2</cell>
                <cell>3</cell>
                <cell>4</cell>
                <cell>5</cell>
                <cell>6</cell>
                <cell>7</cell>
                <cell>8</cell>
                <cell>9</cell>
                <cell>10</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="medium">p</cell>
                <cell>1.0</cell>
                <cell>1.1</cell>
                <cell>1.2</cell>
                <cell>1.5</cell>
                <cell>1.8</cell>
                <cell>2.0</cell>
                <cell>2.3</cell>
                <cell>2.7</cell>
                <cell>3.1</cell>
                <cell>3.5</cell>
                <cell>4.1</cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
        It looks like this data doubles about every five years. The
        starting value is 1. From the notes, I can use the provided
        structure for this exponential function: if <m>a</m> is the
        starting value and <m>d</m> is the doubling period, the
        function should be <m>a2^{\frac{t}{d}}</m>. Using the values from
        this data, here is the exponential function.
        <md>
          p(t) = 2^{\frac{t}{5}}
        </md>
        If I wanted, I could change base to write this as an
        exponential function with base <m>e</m>. (This is useful to do
        in many cases, since the base <m>e</m> is the most common and
        most useful base for exponential functions in calculus.) 
        <md>
          p(t) =  e^{\frac{t \ln 2}{5}}
        </md>
        The following table shows the values of this function to
        compare with the data set. 
        </p>
          <table xml:id="table-data-set-exponential-1-answers">
            <title>Data Set 1 for Exponential Growth - Values</title>
            <tabular>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell right="medium">t</cell>
                <cell>0</cell>
                <cell>1</cell>
                <cell>2</cell>
                <cell>3</cell>
                <cell>4</cell>
                <cell>5</cell>
                <cell>6</cell>
                <cell>7</cell>
                <cell>8</cell>
                <cell>9</cell>
                <cell>10</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="medium">p</cell>
                <cell>1.0</cell>
                <cell>1.1</cell>
                <cell>1.2</cell>
                <cell>1.5</cell>
                <cell>1.8</cell>
                <cell>2.0</cell>
                <cell>2.3</cell>
                <cell>2.7</cell>
                <cell>3.1</cell>
                <cell>3.5</cell>
                <cell>4.1</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="medium"><m>2^\frac{t}{5}</m></cell>
                <cell>1.00</cell>
                <cell>1.14</cell>
                <cell>1.32</cell>
                <cell>1.51</cell>
                <cell>1.74</cell>
                <cell>2.00</cell>
                <cell>2.30</cell>
                <cell>2.64</cell>
                <cell>3.03</cell>
                <cell>3.48</cell>
                <cell>4.00</cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
          <p>
            The function seems reasonably close to the given data.
          </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Here is a dataset. Just by looking at the dataset, guess
          the doubling period and write a guess of the appropriate
          exponential function. Evaluate that exponential function
          (using a calculator or computer) and compare the values with
          the data. 
          <table xml:id="table-data-set-exponential-2">
            <title>Data Set 2 for Exponential Growth</title>
            <tabular>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell right="medium">t</cell>
                <cell>0</cell>
                <cell>1</cell>
                <cell>2</cell>
